title: Relief for Kangana Ranaut as Bombay high court disposes of petition on 'Emergency' release
title_detail: {'type': 'text/plain', 'language': 'en-IN', 'base': 'https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/rssfeeds/-2128838597.cms', 'value': "Relief for Kangana Ranaut as Bombay high court disposes of petition on 'Emergency' release"}
summary: The Bombay High Court resolved a dispute between Zee Entertainment and the CBFC regarding the film "Emergency." The CBFC required 13 changes to issue a UA certificate, and Zee confirmed compliance. The court allowed 30 days for modifications, followed by 14 days for CBFC verification. The film, starring Kangana Ranaut, attracted Sikh group protests.

title_detail: {'type': 'text/plain', 'language': 'en-IN', 'base': 'https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/rssfeeds/-2128838597.cms', 'value': 'Classical language status to Marathi a result of collective efforts, not single party: Shiv Sena (UBT) leader Sanjay Raut'}
summary: Shiv Sena (UBT) leader Sanjay Raut welcomed the Centre's decision to grant classical language status to Marathi, highlighting the collective effort over decades. He noted political motives behind the decision ahead of Maharashtra assembly elections and urged the BJP to address industrial migration from the state. Marathi joins five other languages with classical status in India.

title: Maharashtra subsidy for cows tops Gujarat, Madhya Pradesh and Rajasthan
title_detail: {'type': 'text/plain', 'language': 'en-IN', 'base': 'https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/rssfeeds/-2128838597.cms', 'value': 'Maharashtra subsidy for cows tops Gujarat, Madhya Pradesh and Rajasthan'}
summary: The Mahayuti government in Mumbai approved a daily subsidy of Rs 50 per cow for registered gaushalas, totaling Rs 230 crore annually. This payout exceeds subsidies in other BJP-ruled states. Despite financial concerns, the cabinet overruled the finance department's objection, aiming to support desi cows amid declining numbers. The state already has existing schemes aiding cattle shelters.
